the only thing you 100% need for good pronunciation and pitch is a lot of listening immersion and lots of output and a little bit of self awareness. you can also use some extra tools to speed it up.

all learners, regardless of level but especially beginners, should practice [kotu minimal pairs](https://kotu.io/) build a basic perception of pitch accent. 

If you do Anki, I strongly recommend grading for pitch of individual words. I find that doing this helps me spot a lot of mistakes in my own output, and then I can self correct over time. It also makes sure you learn new words with the correct pitch.

if you do anki i strongly recommend reviewing pitch ontop of readings, as figuring out the pitch of individual words is very time consuming, especially if you are fixing your already existing fucked up pitch

learning the rules associated with pitch from sources such as [dogen](https://mega.nz/folder/sVEizTTb#Z_0QKuN2GyMphaK9w4-A5Q) (more sources will be listed later) could be helpful alongside immersion but i found it boring asf and just kinda gave up idk

shadowing is dead and replaced with chorusing. there are some good videos on how to do that somewhere on youtube and if you are scared of outputting with real people from 0 it might be easier for you to practice on your own like this. not necessary imo but some people have gotten pretty cracked from this

pitch corrected roudoku is also allegedly good for fixing individual pitch mistakes but good luck finding a native speaker who is willing to put up with 100000 hours of you sounding retarded 

the whole idea of a language parent is kind of stupid, but choosing a dialect to speak in (hyoujungo for most people) is probably a good idea.
